'''Gerontissa Gavrielia''' (Elder Gabriela), also known as '''Mother Gavrielia'''<ref name="In Communion"/> (15 October 1897 – 28 March 1992) was a [[Greek Orthodox Church|Greek Orthodox]] nun, known for her care of the poor and sick. She was the second woman to be admitted to a Greek university and was a trained physiotherapist prior to taking up her religious calling at the age of 60.

==Biography==
Avrilia Papayannis<ref name="In Communion">{{cite journal|last1=Brady|first1=John|title=Mother Gavrilia: "A Holocaust to His Love"|journal=In Communion|date=Fall 2004|issue=35|url=http://incommunion.org/2004/10/23/mother-gavrilia/|accessdate=8 December 2015|publisher=Orthodox Peace Fellowship|location=Alkmaar, The Netherlands}}</ref> was born on 15 October (2 October [[Old Style and New Style dates|O.S.]]) 1897 N.S. in [[Constantinople]] in the [[Ottoman Empire]]<ref name="Russian Orthodox archive">{{cite web|title=Gerontissa (Elder) Gabrielia |url=http://www.stjohndc.org/Russian/saints/SaintsE/e_0110c.htm |publisher=Russian Orthodox Cathedral of St. John the Baptist |accessdate=8 December 2015 |location=Washington, D.C. |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126003728/http://www.stjohndc.org/Russian/saints/SaintsE/e_0110c.htm |archivedate=26 January 2016 |df= }}</ref> as the youngest child of Helias and Victoria Papayannis,<ref name=OrthodoxWiki>{{cite web|title=Gabrielia (Papayannis)|url=http://orthodoxwiki.org/Gabrielia_%28Papayannis%29|publisher=OrthodoxWiki|accessdate=8 December 2015|date=11 February 2015}}</ref> a wealthy Greek family. She grew up in Constantinople and lived there until her family was deported during the 1923 [[population exchange between Greece and Turkey]] and sent to [[Thessaloniki]]. She entered the [[Aristotle University of Thessaloniki]], becoming the second woman ever admitted to a Greek university,<ref name="In Communion" /> where she earned a degree in [[philosophy]]. She had previously graduated with a degree in [[botany]] at a Swiss university.{{sfn|Karellos|2001|p=23}} In 1932, she moved to Athens and cared for [[nursing home]] residents<ref name="In Communion" /> until 1938 when she moved to England to study [[podiatry]] and [[physiotherapy]], where she remained until the end of [[World War II]].<ref name="Russian Orthodox archive" />

==Career==
In 1945, Papayannis returned to Greece and began working with the [[American Farm School]] and [[Friends Relief Service]] in Thessaloniki,{{sfn|Marder|1979|p=215}}<ref name="Russian Orthodox archive" /> until 1947, when she moved to Athens and opened a physiotherapy practice. For a decade she operated her office using funds from her paying clients to provide assistance to the poor. Upon the death of her mother, in 1954, she took a vow of poverty and gave all her worldly possessions away. The following year,<ref name="In Communion" /> she moved to [[India]] to work with the poor and assist [[Baba Amte]] in his work with [[Leprosy|leper]] communities in India.<ref name=OrthodoxWiki /> After four years of providing free physiotherapy to the poor, Papayannis went to the [[Himalayan Mountains]], spending eleven months in solitude as a hermit.<ref name="In Communion" /> She then traveled to [[Landour]] where she met an American woman, who arranged for her to go to the monastery headed by Father Theodosius in [[Bethany]], in the [[Holy Land]] in 1960.{{sfn|Karellos|2001|p=25}} She arrived at the [[Bethany Community of the Resurrection of the Lord]]{{#tag:ref|The Russian Orthodox archive account calls this monastery the "Monastery of Mary and Martha",<ref name="Russian Orthodox archive" /> Brady calls it the "Monastery of St. Lazarus"<ref name="In Communion" /> and the Orthodox Wiki calls it "the Monastery of Sts Mary and Martha in Bethany".<ref name=OrthodoxWiki /> The Greek Orthodox Church and St. Lazarus Monastery were not built until 1965.{{sfn|Murphy-O'Connor|2008|p=228}} According to the Russian Ecclesiastical Mission of Jerusalem, two British women, who became Orthodox tonsured nuns in 1932, took the religious names Mary and Martha. They organized a religious community in Bethany, called the Bethany Community of the Resurrection of the Lord. Soon after its founding, the church authorities moved the community to Gethsemane where they became attached to the [[Church of Mary Magdalene]]. Though its name officially remains the Bethany Community of the Resurrection of the Lord, it is often identified as the Convent of Mary Magdalene.<ref name="Russian Ecclesiastical Mission">{{cite web|title=Bethany Community of the Resurrection of the Lord|url=http://www.jerusalem-mission.org/bethany.html|publisher=Russian Ecclesiastical Mission|accessdate=8 December 2015|location=Jerusalem, Israel}}</ref>|group="notes"}} and after accepting [[tonsure]] became a nun. After her three-year [[novitiate]], Papayannis took the name Gavrielia.<ref name="In Communion" />

Sister Gavrielia was sent to the [[Taizé Community]] in France by the Patriarch [[Athenagoras I of Constantinople]], though her assignment there was brief. She was then sent to the United States, where she toured ethnic Greek communities in seventeen states and accompanied many mentally ill patients to psychiatric hospitals in Europe.{{sfn|Karellos|2001|pp=25–26}} After nearly a decade of touring, speaking, and helping the sick, she was sent to East Africa for three years to do missionary work.<ref name="In Communion" /> Following a brief assignment in Germany, Sister Gavrielia was sent back to India,{{sfn|Karellos|2001|pp=25–26}} where she remained for three years. In 1979, she was given use of an Athens apartment and became a "Gerontissa" (elder), counseling disciples and helping the sick over the next ten years. Near the end of her life, she retreated to a hermitage in [[Aegina]],<ref name="In Communion" /> but when she developed [[Hodgkin's disease]] she returned to Athens. After a miraculous healing, she left Athens two years before her death and moved to the island of [[Leros]].{{sfn|Karellos|2001|pp=25–26}} Gerontissa Gavrielia died on Leros on 28 March, 1992.<ref name="Russian Orthodox archive" />

== Legacy ==
In 1996 a biography of her life entitled ''I Askitiki tis Agapis'' was published in Greek,<ref name="Russian Orthodox archive" /> in 1999 the book was translated into English,{{sfn|Nun Gavrilia|1999|p=}} and in 2000 into Russian.<ref name="Russian Orthodox archive" /> It has since had 14 Greek editions, 2 English editions, and has been translated into Arabic, French and Serbian.{{sfn|Karellos|2001|p=21}}

